snippet.textDisplay:
As a graduate student in the nursing program in the Midwest in addition to being married to a current ICU nurse working at a local hospital, people's health is our priority. Sooner or later, my wife will be working with those who are positive to COVID-19. It is unavoidable. We both know of the risks involve and are willing to put our lives on the line to help others who are sick.
To go off tangent a bit, my wife and I were out shopping at our local grocery store late tonight and the most disheartening thing happened. The looks we got from other people and their families. The way people would backtrack and walk around us in the fruit aisle rather than walk past us or laugh amongst themselves upon seeing us. I didn't think much about it but after it occurred more than twice throughout our shopping trip, it hit me that what I have been seeing on the internet has been true all along. The stigma associated with Asians and the coronavirus is more than real.
With nothing but the utmost respect, I want non-Asian people to understand that even though Asians all look alike, we may all not be Chinese. There are hundreds if not thousands of different ethnicities that fall under the Asian race. In fact, the term Chinese basically means someone who was born in the country of China. It is not an ethnic group. Aside from that, even if my wife and I were Chinese nationals, which we are not, that is not enough to warrant hate and disgust towards us or anyone who happens to look like us because we look Chinese.
Long story short, for those who are afraid or just simply full of hate, please remember that if or when one of your love ones is in the hospital, it will be people like my wife and me who would be tending to your love one’s every need. It would be us who will make sure that your loved one fully responds to the care provided. Last but not least, it would be us who will make sure that you get to go home with your loved one. Please stay positive and optimistic. God bless!
